"""
Pester - A Process Management Tool for Testing and Automation

⚠️ WARNING: This tool is designed for educational and testing purposes only.
Use it responsibly and only on systems you own or have explicit permission to test.

Description:
-----------
Pester is a Python class that provides two main functionalities:
1. Launch programs periodically at specified intervals
2. Block (kill) specific processes by name

Requirements:
------------
- Python 3.6 or higher
- psutil library: pip install psutil

Basic Usage:
-----------
from pester import Pester

# Create an instance
p = Pester()

# Launch Firefox every 2 seconds
p.launch_every("firefox", "2 seconds")

# Launch Notepad every 10 seconds (Windows)
p.launch_every("notepad", "10 seconds")

# Block any process containing "firefox" in its name
p.block("firefox")

# Block VS Code
p.block("Code")

# Block Paint (Windows)
p.block("mspaint")

# Start the pestering!
p.start()

How It Works:
------------
1. launch_every(): 
   - Finds the executable path automatically (using shutil.which)
   - Launches the program using subprocess.Popen()
   - Re-launches it at the specified interval

2. block():
   - Monitors all running processes
   - Kills any process whose name contains the specified substring
   - Checks every 0.3 seconds

Supported Time Formats:
---------------------
- '500 milliseconds' or '500ms'
- '5 seconds' or '5s'
- '2 minutes' or '2m'
- '1 hour' or '1h'

Example:
--------
p.launch_every("calc", "30 seconds")  # Open calculator every 30 seconds

Platform Support:
----------------
- Windows: Works with .exe files (extension is optional)
- Linux: Works with executable names (firefox, gedit, etc.)
- macOS: Works with app names (Safari, etc.)

Stopping the Program:
-------------------
- Press Ctrl+C to stop the pestering
- All background threads will be terminated

⚠️ Important Notes:
-------------------
1. This tool can be disruptive if used maliciously
2. Use it only on your own computer
3. The block function will forcefully terminate processes without saving data
4. Some processes may have restrictions (AccessDenied error)
5. The program does NOT run on GitHub Pages - it must be executed locally

Troubleshooting:
---------------
- If a program doesn't launch, try providing the full path:
  p.launch_every("C:/Program Files/Firefox/firefox.exe", "5 seconds")

- If you see AccessDenied errors, try running with administrator/sudo privileges

- On Linux/macOS, you may need to use the exact executable name:
  p.launch_every("firefox", "2 seconds")
  p.launch_every("gedit", "5 seconds")

